<h1>To Francis Dana</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">My dear Friend</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Hague, Hotel des Etats Unis de L Amerique,<br/>May 13. 1782</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Yours of April 12/23<a class="ptr" href="#PJA13d021n1" id="PJA13d021n1-ptr">1</a> is just come to hand: Last night, for the first time, I Slept in this House, and I hope that the Air of the Hague will have a good Effect upon my Health, otherwise I must embark for the blue Hills.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA13d021n2" id="PJA13d021n2-ptr">2</a></p>
<p>The Independance of America, has been acknowledged by this Republick, with a Solemnity and Unanimity, which has made it, in a peculiar Sense the National Act. The Publication of the Memorial of the 19 of April 1781,<a class="ptr" href="#PJA13d021n3" id="PJA13d021n3-ptr">3</a> Sett all the Writers of Gazettes and Pamphlets to work to propagate and illustrate the Hints thrown out by it, so that in the Course of a years time, the People were universally convincd and their Zeal was animated, to such a Degree, that When the Plott came to its unravelling, they threw out Testimonies and Arguments in their Requetes which must do great service to the American Cause. The Ennemy have perceived this, and have done all they could, to prevent an Extensive Publication of them.</p>
<p>Pray let me know what Gazettes or periodical Papers are published with you and in what Languages, and whether there is any Indulgence to the Press with you.</p>
<p>I have laid before their H. M. a Plan of a Treaty, which I hear no objection to, and am told by the grand Pensionary will be settled in about 2 Weeks. The other matter is not yet Stirred. I shall wait for the advice of allies in this Case, although I ventured to go against it, in the former.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA13d021n4" id="PJA13d021n4-ptr">4</a></p>
<p>Once in my Life, the Words <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Piddling</span> &amp;c cost me, very dear:<a class="ptr" href="#PJA13d021n5" id="PJA13d021n5-ptr">5</a> but I Shall never get them out of my Head: I shall be plagued with Piddling Politicians as long as I live: at least, untill I retire from the Political Career to the blue Hills. There are at this Moment So many Politicians piddling about Peace, general, and Seperate, that I am Sick to death of it. Why is there not one Soul in Europe, capable of Seeing the plainest Thing in the World. Any one of the neutral Powers, Saying to the Rest,</p>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="ADMS-06-13-02-pb-0022">[22]</span>
<p>America is one of us, and We will all Share in her Commerce. Let us all as one declare it.</p>
<p>These Words once pronounced, Peace is made, or at least Soon and easily made. Without it all may nibble and piddle and dribble and fribble: waste a long time, immense Treasures and much human Blood. And they must come to it at last.</p>
<p>The new British Ministers blunder at first Setting out. They had but one System to choose, which could succeed and that they have missed.</p>
<p>They must come to it, finally: but it will be after an opposition Shall be formed and cemented, which will give them much trouble and make them unpopular.</p>
<p>No News from America, a long time, except of the Safe Arrival of my dear Charles.</p>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="PJA13d021sn1">

   <p>
<span class="docSource"><span class="dType"><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ recipients copy (A recipients copy is assumed to be in the hand of the signer unless it is otherwise described.) ]">RC</abbr></span> (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Massachusetts Historical Society ]">MHi</span>: Dana Family Papers); endorsed: Mr. Adamss Letter Dated May 13th. 1782. Recd. Aug: 24th. OS.</span>
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA13d021n1-ptr" id="PJA13d021n1">1</a>

   <p>vol. <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-12-02-0296" class="document">12:455457</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA13d021n2-ptr" id="PJA13d021n2">2</a>

   <p><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> also announced his move to the new American legation in letters to <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Quincy Adams (17671848), son of John and Abigail Adams ]">JQA</abbr> of <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-04-04-02-0215" class="document">13 May</a> and to <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Abigail Adams (17441818), m. John Adams 1764 ]">AA</abbr> of the <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-04-04-02-0216" class="document">14th</a>, and on <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-04-04-02-0217" class="document">16 June</a> he wrote his wife that the Air of the Hague, and the Return of warm Weather, tho later than was ever known, is of great Service to my Health (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;Adams Family Correspondence&lt;/i&gt;, ed. L. H. Butterfield, Marc Friedlaender, Richard Alan Ryerson, Margaret A. Hogan, and others, Cambridge, 1963?. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">AFC</span></span>, 4:322325). The blue Hills refers to Braintree, Mass., <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr>s home.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA13d021n3-ptr" id="PJA13d021n3">3</a>

   <p>Vol. <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-11-02-0204" class="document">11:272282</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA13d021n4-ptr" id="PJA13d021n4">4</a>

   <p>The other matter upon which <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> would wait for advice was presumably the proposed triple alliance between the United States, France, and the Netherlands (or quadruple if Spain were to be added). In his <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-13-02-0201" class="document">5/16 Sept.</a> response to this letter, below, Dana asked <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> about the matter upon which he had gone against the advice of his French allies and assumed that it was regarding the presentation, on <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-12-02-0118" class="document">9 Jan. 1782</a>, of his demand that the States General respond to his <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-11-02-0205" class="document">19 April 1781</a> memorial (vol. 12:175, 186191). For <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr>s explanation of his meaning, see his letter to Dana of <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-13-02-0241" class="document">10 Oct.</a>, below.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA13d021n5-ptr" id="PJA13d021n5">5</a>

   <p><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> characterized John Dickinson as a certain great Fortune and piddling Genius in a letter to James Warren of <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-03-02-0052" class="document">24 July 1775</a> that was captured by the British and printed in various American and English newspapers (vol. 3:8993). <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> referred to Dickinsons influence on the faction in the Continental Congress that opposed decisive action against the British in the wake of the battles of Lexington and Concord and Bunker Hill. For the effect of this indiscretion on <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr>, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-13-02-0041&amp;expandNote=PJA13d055n6#PJA13d055n6" class="document">note 6</a> to that letter.</p>

</div>
</div>
